        "title": "Solving Modulus Inequalities",
        "digitizedText": "## 4.4 Solving Modulus Inequalities\nThe logic for modulus inequalities relies heavily on the distance interpretation of the modulus.\n\n### Standard Forms\n1. **$|f(x)| < a$** (where $a > 0$):\n   This means the distance is less than $a$.\n   $$-a < f(x) < a$$\n2. **$|f(x)| > a$** (where $a > 0$):\n   This means the distance is strictly greater than $a$.\n   $$f(x) < -a \\quad \\text{or} \\quad f(x) > a$$\n\n\n\n### Inequalities with Modulus on Both Sides\nFor inequalities of the form $|f(x)| > |g(x)|$ or $|f(x)| < |g(x)|$, the most reliable method is to **square both sides**. Because both sides are non-negative, the direction of the inequality sign is preserved.",
