        "digitizedText": "# Chapter 11: Permutations and Combinations\n\n## 11.1 Basic Counting Principles\n\nIn combinatorics, the fundamental counting principles help determine the number of possible outcomes for multiple events.\n\n### The Addition Rule (The \"OR\" Rule)\nIf an event can occur in $m$ ways and a second, mutually exclusive event can occur in $n$ ways, then the total number of ways either of the events can occur is $m + n$.\n\n### The Multiplication Rule (The \"AND\" Rule)\nIf a sequence of events consists of one event that can occur in $m$ ways, followed by a second independent event that can occur in $n$ ways, the total number of ways the sequence can occur is $m \\times n$.",
