        "digitizedText": "## 12.2 Arithmetic Progressions\nAn Arithmetic Progression (AP) is a sequence in which the difference between any two consecutive terms is a constant. This constant is called the common difference, denoted by $d$.\n\n### Important Variables\n*   $a$ = first term ($u_1$)\n*   $d$ = common difference ($u_{n} - u_{n-1}$)\n*   $n$ = number of terms\n*   $u_n$ = the $n$-th term\n*   $S_n$ = the sum of the first $n$ terms\n\n### The $n$-th Term of an AP\nThe formula to find any specific term in an arithmetic progression is:\n$$u_n = a + (n - 1)d$$\n\n\n\n### The Sum to $n$ Terms of an AP\nTo find the sum of the first $n$ terms of an AP, use either of the following formulas depending on the given information:\n$$S_n = \\frac{n}{2}[2a + (n - 1)d]$$\nAlternatively, if the last term $l$ is known:\n$$S_n = \\frac{n}{2}(a + l)$$",
